,"0996–Female":"0996–Deceased","0996":"0996","1800":"1800","um 1050":"about 1050","Abt 1052":"about 1052","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","1020":"1020","1052":"1052","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Suisse":"Chêne-Bougeries, Geneva, Switzerland","Of,, Genève, Switzerland":"Geneva, Switzerland","Genève, Genève, Switzerland":"Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bourgogne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile.","Americanized form of French   Bourgoin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourgoin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphee, Alyre, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Celina, Emile, Gilberte, Jacques, Laurent, Lucienne, Olivier.","French:","variant of <b>Bourgouin</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), a habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the Western Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404; duke from 1363). Compare   Bourgoyne   and   Bourguignon  ."]}]},{"name":"Gisèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Gisella","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]},{"name":"Gisele","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]},{"name":"Gisela","meanings":["from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ or ‘scion’.  See  <b>Giselle</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gisèle de Bourgogne was born in 1020, in Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland as the daughter of Willa de Ponthieu. She married Count Gérold DE GENEVE II de Vienne about 1039, in Geneva, Switzerland. She died in 1060, in Chêne-Bougeries, Geneva, Switzerland, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1020–1060":"1020–1060","1015–1800":"1015–1800","1050–1095":"1050–1095","1052–Male":"1052–Surnud","1034–Female":"1034–Surnud","0996–Female":"0996–Surnud","0996":"0996","1800":"1800","um 1050":"umbes 1050","Abt 1052":"umbes 1052","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","1020":"1020","1052":"1052","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Suisse":"Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Šveits","Of,, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Šveits","Genève, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Genève, Šveits"},"fi":{"1020–1060":"1020–1060","1015–1800":"1015–1800","1050–1095":"1050–1095","1052–Male":"1052–Kuollut","1034–Female":"1034–Kuollut","0996–Female":"0996–Kuollut","0996":"0996","1800":"1800","um 1050":"noin 1050","Abt 1052":"noin 1052","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","1020":"1020","1052":"1052","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Suisse":"Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Sveitsi","Of,, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Sveitsi","Genève, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Genève, Sveitsi"},"fr":{"1020–1060":"1020–1060","1015–1800":"1015–1800","1050–1095":"1050–1095","1052–Male":"1052–Décédé","1034–Female":"1034–Décédée","0996–Female":"0996–Décédée","0996":"0996","1800":"1800","um 1050":"environ 1050","Abt 1052":"environ 1052","1015":"1015","1034":"1034","1020":"1020","1052":"1052","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Suisse":"Chêne-Bougeries, Genève, Suisse","Of,, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Suisse","Genève, Genève, Switzerland":"Genève, Genève, Suisse","lifeSummary":"Gisèle de Bourgogne est 